Speakers
 
Susan Hodgett
Deputy Chair of the Research Excellence Framework (REF) sub panel 27 (Area Studies) and Senior Lecturer at Ulster University. Susan has worked with departments of the Government of Canada (currently Global Affairs) and government in Northern Ireland on EU/local policy analysis and had a career in politics before working in academia.
 
Rod Rhodes
Professor of Government (Research) at the University of Southampton, Director of the UK Economic and Social Research Council's 'Whitehall Programme' (1994-1999); and Distinguished Professor of Political Science at the Australian National University (2006-11). Rhodes is well known for his prodigious global research on narrative approaches to policy.

Packs of training materials were given out to participants at the end of the event.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2016</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>0C5BD5E9-44FF-4EA1-ABF5-011988EC7321</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>58bd92dc14a848.81437736</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Healthcare,Government, Democracy and Justice,Transport,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The aim of the project is to recover methodologies from the Arts and Humanities for the use of Political Scientists and interdisciplinary Area (or country) Studies specialists. The Blurring Genres Network is encouraging sharing of best practice necessary to inform future policy-making and innovative scholarly work. The innovative network will encourage interdisciplinary research between scholars in the UK and beyond. The network will organize a research field that, to date, has been unstructured. It is assisting scholars in the United Kingdom to lead the field in this emerging international and interdisciplinary research. It will also connect a number of learned societies (UK Council of Area Studies Associations (UKCASA), Political Studies Association UK (PSA) and the Western Political Science Association (USA) with each other and/or senior UK policy-makers. All seminars, to date, have involved representatives from the member associations of UKCASA, the PSA, and UK policymakers. This report covers progress at the half-way point in our funding. 
Two seminars have been held in 2016 and were considered a great success (see comments below). Four more seminars will be held by the end of 2017.

What were the most significant achievements from the award?
We have organised six workshops: 
 1. Politics as Drama - SOAS, University of London - Tues. 28 June 2016
 2. Policy as Stories and Narratives - SOAS, London - Thurs.17 November 2016 
(*a separate event on Policy Analysis as Narrative was held the day after for Home Office/ Civil Service Learning in Whitehall.) 
 3. Politics as History - Manchester University - Monday 8 May 2017
 4. Politics as Anthropology - SOAS/University of Southampton - Friday 23 June 2017
 5. Politics as Literature - University of California Berkeley - Wednesday 6 September 2017
 6. Politics as Human Affairs and Philosophy - Ulster University - Fri. 17 November 2017 

Two workshops have been held already
1. Politics as Drama - SOAS, University of London - Tues. 28 June 2016

Maarten Hajer, Professor of Urban Futures, University of Utrecht. 
From a &amp;quot;Walk in the Woods&amp;quot; to the &amp;quot;Climate Crisis&amp;quot;: the Importance of understanding Politics as Drama.
Rens van Munster, Senior Researcher, Danish Institute for International Studies.
&amp;quot;Staging World Politics: The Politics and Ideology of Documentary Film.&amp;quot;
Joe Kelleher, Professor of Theatre and Performance, Roehampton University, 
&amp;quot;State of Play: on theatre and the political.&amp;quot;
Discussion on going forward.

Attendees Included 
Ten professors from UK universities including Oxbridge and Russell Group institutions amongst others. Several senior academics from UK institutions. Doctoral students and senior foreign academics attended along with representatives from the Policy Profession UK (Senior Civil Servants). Attendees were equally divided between the Arts and Humanities and the Social Sciences.

Comments from Participants
The first workshop I attended of the Blurring Genes Network was excellent both in terms of its organisation and the range of presenters. The discussion certainly did help to stimulate new avenues of enquiry to be developed and deepened throughout the coming workshops. I was particularly interested in the presentations on visual evidence through documentary film which offered much original thinking and novel approaches. (Professor, Arts and Humanities)

Cross-disciplinary work and thinking is something more often talked about than actually done. In this respect, it was quite something to be in a room not only with politics people but also with specialists in the Middle East, social policy, 'oriental' studies and more. The day was well set up and the audience well chosen The seminar featured three very different kinds of talk connected by the broad themes of performance and narrative. The talks might have had little in common but the focus on politics meant that connections were made clear (and important differences usefully highlighted). Discussions furthered understanding of such commonalities and differences and helped open on to the central theme of the seminar series. I was convinced by the day that there are ways to bring humanities and Political Science into fruitful conversation, for politics to learn from these other perspectives and for them to learn from politics. (Professor, Political Science)

 I found the workshop to be a deeply thoughtful and intellectually lively occasion; as a humanities scholar, I was very interested to hear both the concerns of participating politics scholars on what they wanted to do and felt was missing in their work, and also to hear how much they are already doing that connects with my work and outlook. I also thought the formal contributions were very useful, and - again, from a humanities perspective - they also served as a reminder that whilst we share much and can learn from each other, we also ought not assume that such crossovers can be done with ease (the various uses that 'performance' and associated words have been subject to across the Humanities is a case in point). The day left me full of thoughts and longing to read more of the work that was referred to - I hope this develops not only into an ongoing conversation across disciplines as envisioned but also generates an associated reading group (Professor, Area Studies)

Thanks so much for bringing everyone together yesterday and for selecting three excellent speakers. It was a brilliant start to your network. I have spent the morning distilling my notes and making links between some of the ideas I was introduced to yesterday and my own work. What you are doing is so important for academics. We rarely get the chance to branch out beyond our disciplines. Getting to do this is important both in terms of the new research agendas it could help feed but also the networks and synergies it will foster. Would there be room for a workshop that allows the members of the network to talk about the impact the events are having on their own thoughts about their own work and also about how they understand their discipline and its priorities? (Senior Lecturer, Political Science)

Thank you so much for yesterday's network meeting. It achieved all that I thought it would - it was provoking, it exposed me to colleagues from other genres and how they deal with politics, it challenged the ways I view things and gave me much to think about. It showed, above all, how the need for a 'Blurring Genres Network' is a very real one - and I am really looking forward to participating in the coming months. Thanks again - it was a real intellectual delight. (PhD candidate and former senior politician)

2. Policy as Stories and Narratives - SOAS, London- Thurs. 17 November 2016 
* Second event for Home Office/ Civil Service Learning Friday 18 November 2016

Mark Bevir, (Professor, University of California, Berkeley)
&amp;quot;Opening Remarks&amp;quot;
Susan Hodgett, Senior Lecturer, Ulster University &amp;quot;Feelingful Development: pushing boundaries- trials and tribulations in using novels and storytelling to inform policymaking and analysis.&amp;quot;
Yiannis Gabriel, Professor Organizational Theory, Bath University.
&amp;quot;Nostalgic narratives, conspiracy theories and right wing ideologies: The dangerous consequences of blurring fantasy and fact.&amp;quot;
Sandford Borins, Professor of Public Management University of Toronto, Research Fellow, Harvard University, Kennedy School.
&amp;quot;It's the Way you Tell It: Conflicting Narratives in the 2015 Canadian Election.&amp;quot;
Tony Chafer, Professor, University of Portsmouth (President, UKCASA). 
Comments and discussion on going forward.

Attendees included 
Eleven Professors from UK universities, several other senior academics along with junior Early Career Researcher staff and four Doctoral students, Civil Service Learning and the Office of National Statistics. Attendees were divided between Area Studies, the Humanities and the Social Sciences.

Comments from Participants 
The workshop brought together humanities specialists interested in storytelling and public policy specialists - a rare combination, but an excellent exemplar of what can be achieved by cross-disciplinary working in the humanities and social sciences. (Professor, Area Studies)

The seminar had many benefits for me and I would rate it as an excellent intellectual[event] Both Hodgett and Gabriel's [papers] were very thought-provoking Finally, I had not met any of the people at the seminar before, so it was very useful for me in terms of networking with people who share my interests in narrative, and discussing both substance and methodology. (Professor, Management)

Thanks for inviting me to the event I definitely felt like I was in a very different world focusing on the applications of the research findings for policy purposes while others were more interested in the methods and findings for their own sake. For offering a policy perspective [some] participants were well placed to think how the kinds of research being discussed could be used to inform policy ideas or decision making having come from that worldI thought the presentations were very interesting and gave me a lot of food for thought. (Office for National Statistics) 

The meeting offered a first-class example of the potential for cross-disciplinary research to feed into policy debates. The standard of all the papers was high; and the discussion that followed was in each case stimulating and vigorous. (Professor, History)

As a PhD student who was looking for alternative methods for my ethnographic fieldwork, I found the presentations and indeed the discussions on how narratives can inform policy-making very interesting. My research project is looking at local representations of security and security policy among transnational communities in Africa. I find that the life story approach can be a very useful entry point for my fieldwork. I would like to continue to be updated on the network activities. (PhD. Candidate)

