The organizers have deliberately tried to maintain a balance of disciplines and to include speakers new to UK audiences. We have also striven to achieve a balanced platform in terms of gender and stage of career for speakers and participants.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>To what extent were the award objectives met? 
? Interdisciplinary scholars (senior and junior) have taken part including international experts, those new to the field, &amp;amp; post graduate students. We have had very good participation from doctoral students who, through evaluation, have told us that they have found the meetings very useful. Overwhelmingly the response of attendees from all sectors has been very positive indicating the real and pressing need to bring together people from across the disciplinary and professional divides to learn from each other.

? We have had particular interest from Government Circles. Policy-makers from across several central government departments have taken part. Participants have benefited from considering how research techniques mined from the Arts and Humanities can better inform the process of modern governance. Case studies have been used. The networking aspects of the research seminars have led to two extra events and workshops held for UK government on the use of narratives in policy evaluation for Civil Service Learning (across 15 government departments) and Cabinet Office (seven different units).

If you can, briefly explain why any key objectives were not met. 
Despite invitations sent to think tanks and commercial research organisations we have been disappointed none has, as yet, attended. We are hoping that they may attend future events. 

How might the findings be taken forward and by whom?
The seminars, as they develop, will lead to new research alliances and future research applications across disciplines and sectors. The network will take this forward as the project develops further.

The following developments are already underway: -
? A book proposal profiling outstanding papers from the series (undertaken by the PI and CI).
? Consideration as to how to give the network a permanent web presence through the Centre for Political Ethnography at Southampton University and/or UKCASA (undertaken by the PI, CI and contributing professional associations). 
? A further research grant application in Area Studies with a political ethnography component is under discussion. We are identifying a team to write the proposal (undertaken by the PI, CI and others). 
? Discussions and updates with professional associations and learned societies including UKCASA and the PSA are being undertaken by the PI and CI as we go forward regarding future developments. 
? Discussions with the media are ongoing (PI).</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>3E1761CD-E581-41CD-9B6D-753DECE6214A</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58c8239fbecae9.61714368</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Environment,Government, Democracy and Justice,Security and Diplomacy,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Telling Stories for Analysis and Impact- Cabinet Office - Analysis and Insight Team -Fri 26 August 2016. Dr. Susan Hodgett</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>E178283C-2622-425D-9B22-D94C5507E5E5</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The 22 participants from several units in Cabinet Office reflected on the uses of constructing narratives of their work. A number of the teams discussed that with me how it might be put into practice.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58c8108fd22085.66575194</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:type>Influenced training of practitioners or researchers</gtr:type></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Policy Analysis as Narrative - Telling stories Date &amp;amp; time: 13:30-17:00 Friday 18 November 2016 Location: Admiralty House, Ripley Yard, 26 Whitehall, SW1A 2DY Dr. Susan Hodgett and Prof. RAW Rhodes.</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>02A009F1-2C4E-45A0-A7AB-B9E3E6EAFC31</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58c80dc49d8cc4.98250745</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:type>Influenced training of practitioners or researchers</gtr:type></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput></gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>B4FEB780-5B42-4883-ADBE-CADB0568B8ED</gtr:id><gtr:title>(forthcoming 2017/8) The Rebirth of Area Studies: Challen